---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import d from '../data/site_data.json';
import { frac, cellType } from '../lib/fmt.js';

const title = 'Explore with Claude — Dual-marker discovery';
const description =
  'Browse the Pareto frontier of surface-accessible marker pairs and ask a grounded Claude assistant about any of them. It answers only from the study\'s committed tables.';

const front = d.surface_frontier;
const n = d.nominated;
---
<Base title={title} description={description} page="explore">
  <section class="hero" style="padding-bottom:0.6rem">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">The tool</p>
      <h1>Explore the frontier, and ask about what you see</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        The assistant answers from the study's committed tables, using tools over the markers, the pairs,
        and the gate scores. It cannot tell you a number the tables do not contain, and it is built to say
        so rather than guess. It is powered by Claude and is access-controlled.
      </p>
      <div class="btnrow">
        <a class="btn primary" href="/app" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open in a new tab &rarr;</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <h2>What to look at</h2>
      <p>
        Below is the surface-accessible Pareto frontier: the {front.length} pairs where no other clean
        pair beats them on <i>both</i> coverage floor and worst-case healthy liability. The frontier is a
        trade-off, not a ranking, which is the point. Nothing here tells you how much coverage a
        clinician should trade for how much liability, because that judgement is not in the data.
      </p>

      <div class="tw">
        <table class="fig">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Pair</th>
              <th class="num">Coverage<br /><span class="sub">median</span></th>
              <th class="num">Floor<br /><span class="sub">lower decile</span></th>
              <th class="num">Worst healthy<br /><span class="sub">extra-prostatic</span></th>
              <th>Where the liability sits</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {front.map((p) => {
              const isLead =
                (p.marker_a === 'FOLH1' && p.marker_b === 'STEAP1') ||
                (p.marker_a === 'STEAP1' && p.marker_b === 'FOLH1');
              return (
                <tr class={isLead ? 'lead' : undefined}>
                  <td>
                    <b>{p.marker_a.replace('FOLH1', 'PSMA')} × {p.marker_b.replace('FOLH1', 'PSMA')}</b>
                    {isLead && <span class="pill" style="margin-left:0.5rem">nominated</span>}
                  </td>
                  <td class="num">{frac(p.tumor_median)}</td>
                  <td class="num">{frac(p.tumor_q10)}</td>
                  <td class="num">{frac(p.worst_healthy_xprostate)}</td>
                  <td class="ct">{cellType(p.worst_xp_celltype)}</td>
                </tr>
              );
            })}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p>
        Notice that the nominated pair is neither the top of the coverage column nor the bottom of the
        liability column. Pairs above it cover more tumor and leak more; pairs below it leak less and
        cover almost nothing. It was carried forward because it sits where those two curves cross and
        because both of its antigens already have clinical-grade binders. Ask the assistant why, and it
        will tell you from the tables.
      </p>

      <h2>Questions worth asking it</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Why is {n.pair.replace('FOLH1', 'PSMA').replace(' + ', ' × ')} nominated when STEAP2 × TMPRSS2 covers far more tumor?</li>
        <li>What is the worst healthy tissue for STEAP1 on its own, and what does the gate do to it?</li>
        <li>Which pairs were excluded for label leakage, and why does that disqualify them?</li>
        <li>Did any NOT gate work?</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <div class="container">
      <iframe class="embed" src="/app" title="Explore with Claude" loading="lazy" style="height:90vh"></iframe>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
